<paragraph id="8B96369BFFAAE27735E5ABEBFB1EFF0A" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,609]" pageId="10" pageNumber="532">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="13122A1EFFAAE277346BABEBFE26FF6E" box="[329,415,151,177]" captionStart="FIGS" captionStartId="8.[151,212,1796,1820]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,1174,1771]" captionTargetId="figure-414@8.[151,1436,1173,1773]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGS. 16–22. Aedeagi (not in scale). 16—Anthaxia (Haplathaxia) aethiopica sp. nov., holotype; 17—A. (H.) caerulea sp. nov., holotype; 18—A. (H.) dispar Kerremans, 1898 (RSA, Limpopo); 19—A. (H.) keniae Théry, 1941 (Kenya, Kiserian); 20—A. (H.) komareki Obenberger, 1931, holotype; 21—A. (H.) occidentalis sp. nov., holotype; 22—A. (H.) pilifrons Kerremans, 1898, holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4408013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4408013/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="532">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) widely spindle-shaped, dorsoventrally flattened, parameres deeply constricted at distal third, with rather large, sharp, dorsolateral projection; median lobe obtusely pointed apically.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B96369BFFAAE27735E5ABA3FB40FF26" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,609]" box="[199,1273,222,249]" pageId="10" pageNumber="532">
